,{"id":919191,"guid":"AE8A02F080F311EAA4A93DBDB597EA1B","previous_id":919190,"previous_guid":"AE85E44180F311EAA4A93DBDB597EA1B","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"4B1ED053F8314D8F8BE253CE7EE3D983","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"7278A56C0D0A4C6180A61994B093B225","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Transfer the multiples wells that contain the axenic algae to 15 ml of sterilize fresh media even if they are from the same strain<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":919193,"guid":"AE92DC9080F311EAA4A93DBDB597EA1B","previous_id":919191,"previous_guid":"AE8A02F080F311EAA4A93DBDB597EA1B","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"0F47ABFB684A40FBB39B1B465EB3C0B2","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"715163938D434C80A7646DFADE8CB273","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Cryopreserve immediately the axenic strain if it is possible. For genome sequencing purpose, once the axenic strain is stablished, prepare 1 \u2013 2L of dense culture, collect the cells by centrifugation and freeze at -80 the pellet for future extraction.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":919194,"guid":"FD6822D080F311EAA4A93DBDB597EA1B","previous_id":919184,"previous_guid":"AE793A1080F311EAA4A93DBDB597EA1B","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2E73D6C1646248D7ABE9B099C02D2EF8","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"843BAB9CEDA14B949E2D77A205D09978","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Repeat steps 3 and 4 up for 5 \u2013 6x. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">The wash step (3) needs to be optimized depending on the algae. A good balance between how many times the cells are washed, how many algae cells are remained and the efficiency of bacteria removal needs to be check for each algal group and can be done by FC.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Method used to eliminate bacterial contamination of a marine micro-algal culture. Note, this method is not guaranteed to be 100% successful either due to the fact that the antibiotic combination is not lethal to the bacteria present or it is possible that the strain may not be capable of prolonged growth without the presence of bacteria. This method is based on that of Droop, adapted according to Andersen  but using a modern antibiotic mix suggested by S. Slocombe (SAMS - Scottish Association for Marine Science). The method described here have been successfully used by Christian Jeanthon (ECOMAP) to produce axenic cultures of diatoms and E. huxleyi.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">1. Droop, M. R. A procedure for routine purification of algal cultures with antibiotics. Br. Phycol. Bull. 3, 295\u2013297 (1967).<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">2. Andersen, R. Algal Cultering Techniques. (Academic Press, 2005).<\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1587160044}